{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"80397175-6bca-4b90-82ea-c69de7eac158","content":"The report confirms the overhead is **MSBuild process startup and project re-evaluation**, not compilation itself. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild server node. Here's how to close that gap on the CLI:\n\n### 1. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop (biggest win)\nKeeps the build host alive and only rebuilds on file changes—no repeated process startup:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 2. Enable the MSBuild Server\nReuses MSBuild nodes across CLI invocations (mirrors what VS does). Set this in your shell profile:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\n### 3. Enable Reference Assemblies\nAdd to the `.csproj` so downstream projects can skip unnecessary rebuilds when only method bodies change:\n```xml\n<ProduceReferenceAssembly>true</ProduceReferenceAssembly>\n```\n\n### 4. Use `-tl` (Terminal Logger, .NET 8+)\n```bash\ndotnet build -tl\n```\nEnables the modern terminal logger which also opts into the MSBuild server, combining benefits.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The 2–4 s overhead is almost entirely cold-start cost. `dotnet watch build` eliminates it for edit-build-test cycles; the MSBuild server (`-tl` or env var) eliminates it for ad-hoc `dotnet build` calls. No project file changes are strictly required—it's a CLI invocation pattern issue, not a project configuration issue.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5928f547-1d9a-484e-b154-d5e501c724b3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer's problem is clear: `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds) even when nothing has changed, while Visual Studio builds nearly instantly. The overhead comes from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio keeps an MSBuild server process running (it uses a long-lived MSBuild node), so it avoids the startup cost. The CLI, by default, starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n\nThere are several recommendations:\n\n1. **Use `dotnet build-server`** - .NET SDK ships with an MSBuild server that can be reused across builds. \n\n2. **Enable the MSBuild server with `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`** - This environment variable keeps the MSBuild process alive between builds, eliminating the re-startup overhead that plagues CLI builds.\n\n3. **Use `dotnet watch`** - For development workflows, this keeps the build server warm and automatically rebuilds on file changes.\n\n4. **Graph-based builds with `-graph`** - Can optimize multi-project solutions.\n\n5. **Use terminal logger** - The `-tl` flag can also help with build performance.\n\nThe MSBuild server is really the key here—it's the most direct solution to the startup cost problem, especially in .NET 8 where it's available but might not be enabled by default for CLI builds.\n\nFor practical recommendations, `dotnet watch` is ideal for the inner loop since it keeps the process alive between builds, while enabling the MSBuild server via the environment variable handles the broader case. I should also mention that `<ProduceReferenceAssembly>true</ProduceReferenceAssembly>` can help downstream projects avoid unnecessary rebuilds when only implementation details change.","outputTokens":1188},"id":"120e9b5c-a702-4372-8381-50dc9ff3e5e2","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:49:58.591Z","parentId":"9216096c-96a3-4da9-beee-3e962266f886"}
